#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cwindows_keystrokes_for_text-an.htm%2Bhtml.body.h2:18-1
msgid "General Notes"
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cwindows_keystrokes_for_text-an.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:19-1
msgid ""
"Many of these keystrokes are designed to move the caret (also called the "
"insertion point) in a document as indicated. For many of these keystrokes, "
"JAWS adds the functionality of reading the element to which the caret is "
"moved, i.e., character, word, or paragraph. When <b>SHIFT</b> is added to the "
"keystroke, the text from the caret's original position to its new position "
"will be selected. This does not work reliably with the keystrokes for moving "
"by paragraph, though. JAWS also adds support for using many of these "
"keystrokes with the JAWS, Invisible, and virtual PC cursors. The JAWS and "
"Invisible cursors can only read text already on the screen; they cannot "
"scroll a document in the manner the PC cursor or Virtual PC cursor can."
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cwindows_keystrokes_for_text-an.htm%2Bhtml.body.h2:20-1
msgid "Keystroke Specific Notes"
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cwindows_keystrokes_for_text-an.htm%2Bhtml.body.h3:21-1
msgid "Select All (CTRL+A)"
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cwindows_keystrokes_for_text-an.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:22-1
msgid "This keystroke will not work in all applications."
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cwindows_keystrokes_for_text-an.htm%2Bhtml.body.h3:23-1
msgid "Undo (CTRL+Z)"
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cwindows_keystrokes_for_text-an.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:24-1
msgid ""
"This keystroke can be very useful, especially in text fields in dialog boxes. "
"However, not all actions can be undone, so this keystroke will not always "
"work."
msgstr ""

